  • Column e is not required as it does not carry any information.
  • start_year and end_year are character which needs to be converted to integer.
  • tunnel_per is character which needs to be converted to double after removing % from each rows.
  • real cost is character which needs to be converted to double.


Removing column e and changing type of all the above mentioned columns.

Univariate Analysis with one categorical variable


transit_cost %>% 
  drop_na(country) %>% 
  ggplot()+
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = country), color = "white")+
  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size = 5))+
  labs(title = "Project count for countries",
       y = "Projects",
       x = "Country")+
  coord_flip()

Using proportion in the above plot

transit_cost %>% 
  drop_na(country) %>% 
  ggplot()+
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = country, y = ..prop.., group = 1), color = "white")+
  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size = 5))+
  labs(title = "Project count for countries",
       x = "Country",
       y = "Proportion")+
  coord_flip()


Based on above plot it can be said that China and India are the top two countries in which majority of transit lines are being constructed, however China accounts for more than 50% of total projects.
Since there are too many unique variables in this plot, it becomes very difficult to get information on all the countries. So to get a clear idea on the trend, top 10 countries based on Transit line projects are plotted in below plot.

Univariate Analysis with one numeric variable


plt1 <- ggplot(transit_cost)+
  geom_histogram(aes(length), fill = "orange", color = "black")+
  labs(title = "Transit line length distribution in KM")

plt2 <- ggplot(transit_cost)+
  geom_boxplot(aes(length), outlier.color = "red", fill = "light yellow")

egg::ggarrange(plt1, plt2, heights = 2:1)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.


Median

median(transit_cost$length, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 15.7

IQR

IQR(transit_cost$length, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 22.35


Transit line length distribution plot displayed above indicates that a large number of projects total length falls under 20km.
According to the box plot all the values after 60 can be called as outliers, but they will not be considered as noise as it is very normal for some transits to be of more length compared with other transits.
Above distribution is Right skewed and Unimodal. Since it is skewed, for clear visualization of the data it is better to do a log transformation, which is displayed in below plot.
Central tendency of this distribution will be Median which is equal to 15.7 and spread will be IQR i.e.22.35, as it is often more helpful for skewed distribution to use Median and IQR as central tendency and measure of spread.

Log Transformation

ggplot(transit_cost)+
  geom_histogram(aes(length), fill = "orange", color = "black")+
  labs(title = "Log distribution Transit line length ")+
  scale_x_log10()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.


This distribution shape is close to bell curve and hence it is more easy to visualize.

cor(transit_cost$length, transit_cost$real_cost)
## [1] 0.7478688

Relationship between Countries and transit length cannot be explained properly if we do not know the relationship between transit length and its construction cost. From the above scatter plot we can say that with increase in Transit length the cost of construction also increases. Large amount of points can be seen concentrated near the origin of the plot where transit length is less than 50km and construction cost is below 25000 million USD. There are very few transits where the cost of its construction is above 40000 million USD. And only one case where the transit length is around 125km which is not the longest one but have highest construction cost of more than 90000 million USD, which can also be called as an outlier.
Relationship between both the variable is linear and its direction is positive.
Correlation value for the above plot is 0.7478688 which is a strong relationship.
